# Direct to store orders and cross dock orders

We look at ORDHEAD and ALLOC_HEADER tables and only work on the records with STATUS = 'A'.

Active_ORDHEAD = ORDHEAD WHERE STATUS = 'A'

Active_ALLOC_HEADER = ALLOC_HEADER WHERE STATUS = 'A'

Then, we split the orders into two sections:

Active_ALLOC_HEADER = ALLOC_HEADER WHERE STATUS = 'A'

Then, we split the orders into two sections:

1. Direct Orders: If an order has an ORDER_NO which is seen in the Active_ORDHEAD but not in the Active_ALLOC_HEADER, we take this order into account as a direct order. We look at ORDLOC table just for the orders listed in Direct Orders. -> Direct_Order_ORDLOCWe write incoming stock for ITEM-LOCATION combinations that are stated in the Direct_Order_ORDLOC. IncomingStockFromSupplier is calculated as QTY_ORDERED - QTY_RECEIVED
2. Cross Dock Orders: If an order in Active_ALLOC_HEADER has a not null ORDER_NO, we take this order into account as a cross dock order.We look at ALLOC_DETAIL table just for orders listed in Cross Dock Orders.-> Cross_Dock_Order_ALLOC_DETAILWe write incoming stock for ITEM-TO_LOC combinations where ITEM stated in Cross Dock Orders and TO_LOC stated in the Cross_Dock_Order_ALLOC_DETAIL.IncomingStockFromCrossDock is calculated as QTY_ALLOCATED - QTY_TRANSFERRED

_Dock_Order_ALLOC_DETAIL.IncomingStockFromCrossDock is calculated as QTY_ALLOCATED - QTY_TRANSFERRED

# Handling Negative Values in the Inventory Position Calculation

The system will sum NetStock and NetIncomingStock first, and then it will take the maximum with zero. TotalNetStock = MAX( (NetStock+NetIncomingStock), 0)

For the subitem relations, each item will do this calculation separately and then the inventory will be summed by item family.

Example: An SKU-Store combination

a) NetStock = 5 & NetIncomingStock = 3

TotalNetStock = 8

b) NetStock = -5 & NetIncomingStock = 5

TotalNetStock = 0

c) NetStock = -20 & NetIncomingStock = 5

TotalNetStock = 0

d) NetStock = -5 & NetIncomingStock = 12

TotalNetStock = 7

NetIncomingStock = 5

TotalNetStock = 0

d) NetStock = -5 & NetIncomingStock = 12

TotalNetStock = 7

Example: An item family, P1 and P2 are in the same family

a) P1: NetStock = 5 & NetIncomingStock = 3 TotalStock = 8 before merging family stocks

P2: NetStock = 2 & NetIncomingStock = 4 TotalStock = 6 before merging family stocks

TotalNetStock = 14 for P1 and P2 after merging family stocks

b) P1: NetStock = -5 & NetIncomingStock = 5 TotalStock = 0 before merging family stocks

P2: NetStock = 2 & NetIncomingStock = 4 TotalStock = 6 before merging family stocks

TotalNetStock = 6 for P1 and P2 after merging family stocks

c) P1: NetStock = -15 & NetIncomingStock = 3 TotalStock = 0 before merging family stocks

P2: NetStock = 2 & NetIncomingStock = 4 TotalStock = 6 before merging family stocks

TotalNetStock = 6 for P1 and P2 after merging family stocks

New departments
For the new departments, department analyst will select the replenishment candidate items and fill the standard excel file with some necessary fields such as model after code, seasonality reference. If it is expected to have the item in stores more than 6 months, that item can be a good candidate for replenishment. You can find the template excel here

Current departments

# Store-Item Selection Process

After selecting the combinations, SKU-Store combinations which have never received the initial inventory push will be filtered out. Also, the stores have to be on the list which is written here, Store Selection Process.

# Lead Time Calculation

There should be four different shipment logistics:

#### DC to STORE:

If there is an inventory in Warehouse

LocationType= S & StockCAT= W

WH_LEAD_TIME column from repl item loc

#### SUPPLIER to STORE:

If we dont keep inventory in WH and supplier ships the inventory directly to store

LocationType=S & StockCAT= D

If SUPP_LEAD_TIME is available:

SUPP_LEAD_TIME + PICKUP_LEAD_TIME from repl item loc

If SUPP_LEAD_TIME in repl item loc is not available but LEAD_TIME from item supp country is available :

SUPP_LEAD_TIME in repl item loc is not available but LEAD_TIME from item supp country is available :

LEAD_TIME + PICKUP_LEAD_TIME from item supp country

#### SUPPLIER to DC:

If Supplier sends inventory to WH

LocationType= W & StockCAT=W

SUPP_LEAD_TIME + PICK_LEAD_TIME from repl item loc

#### SUPPLIER to DC to STORE:

If the system creates order to Supplier and it ships to WH and then it goes to Stores (combination of 3 & 1)  PO allocation

Lead time will be Leadtime #1 +Leadtime #3

That means:

If SUPP_LEAD_TIME or WH_LEAD_TIME from repl item loc is available:

SUPP_LEAD_TIME + PICK_UP_LEAD_TIME + WH_LEAD_TIME from repl item loc

If they are not available:

LEAD_TIME + PICKUP_LEAD_TIME from item supp country

# Cover Period Calculation

Cover Period = Lead Time + Review CycleLead time details is [here](https://invent.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/ASOCS/pages/837156869/Store+Replenishment+Module#StoreReplenishmentModule-LeadTimeCalculation)The system uses a review cycle to understand what is the next time that we can give another order. For example, if the item is from DC and the store gets a shipment truck every day, then the review cycle will be 1 day.In general, these are the current review cycles,For the XDock items, the system can create an order once a week, so the review cycle is 7 days.For the DC items, the system can create order every day however there is a store truck schedule. Some stores can get a shipment every day, some stores can get a shipment once a week. If it is every day, then the review cycle is 1, if it is once a week, then the review cycle is 7 days.The system will optimize the inventory level for the cover period.
## Lead Time and Cover Period Minimum & Maximum Caps

imize the inventory level for the cover period.
## Lead Time and Cover Period Minimum & Maximum Caps

The objective of these caps is making sure the parameters are in the excepted range. For the lead time information which is not an acceptable range, the user can see them in lead time exception[report](https://invent.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/ASOCS/pages/905740289/Reporting+Guideline#ReportingGuideline-LeadTimeAlertReport)and we will expect from the user to fix it or inform the hub team if the numbers are accurate so we can stop capping those.

For DC items, minimum lead time value: shared via daily automated email

For Xdock items, the minimum lead time value is : shared via daily automated email

Minimum Cover time in the system can be : shared via daily automated email

Maximum Cover time in the system can be : shared via daily automated email

Question: What makes an item eligible for Invent Store Replenishment?

Answer:

1. Items must be submitted through the hub team

1. If reducing door count, maintain ranging (item loc table) to reflect the new door count
2. If increasing the door count, make sure you made the initial inventory push to new stores. Invent will take those stores to replenishment automatically.

Question: How is Oracle store replenishment different from Invent store replenishment?

Answer:

The main difference is, Invent replenishment is not rule-based. Invent doesn't have weeks of supply rule or Min-Max rule when engine calculates Targets. Invent engine calculates Optimal Inventory Target to cover the sales until next replenishment cycle. Optimal target is affected by Item Forecast, Item Forecast Volatility, and Item Margin.

3. Strategy Communication Protocol

Question: How does the SOQ logic works for constrained inventory in the DC?

Answer:

- If there is zero OH in the DC, then all stores get an SOQ of 0
- If there is constrained inventory in the DC, thensome stores get a positive SOQ, the rest get an SOQ of 0.
- If there is unconstrained inventory in the DC, thenwe just send targets and let RMS calculate the transfers.

Oracle Casepack logic: Oracle roundup first casepack qty if the inventory is less than target. after that, rounds based on the threshold.

# 1) DC-Item Scope:

## Item-DC Scope Selection

- ITEM_LOC: ITEM-DC STATUS = 'A' AND CLEAR_IND = 'N'
- REPL_ITEM_LOC: Warehouse active records with store category records set to W and a transaction. If a warehouse active record is in REPL_ITEM_LOC, but all stores are set to C or D, then it will not be in scope. Also, if stores haven't had any transactions,Invent will generate warehouse orders based on the presentation level because the stores do not have a forecast. ASO has to manage the first order to warehouse. The system will also honor:Deactivate DateActivate Date
- Invent Logic: # of Invent active stores linked to DC >= 1 (Invent active: already in Store RPL scope)

# 2) Forecasting Time Horizon:

Obey store level start date (activate date) and DC level start date (activate date). Max date (latest date) will be used as the start date.
Obey store level end date (deactivate date) and DC level end date (deactivate date). Min date (earliest date) will be used as the end date.

ate) and DC level end date (deactivate date). Min date (earliest date) will be used as the end date.

# 3) Lead Time & Cover Time calculation:

Main calculation:

For Lead Time calculations, the information in REPL_ITEM_LOC Table is used:

DC Lead Time is calculated by the formula below:

*DC_Lead_Time = Supplier_Lead_Time + Pick_Up_Lead_Time +Wh Inbound Handling Days + Shipping window delay*

DC Cover Time is calculated by the formula below:

*Cover_Time =DC_Lead_Time + Review_Cycle(weeks)*Assumptions:

e is calculated by the formula below:

*Cover_Time =DC_Lead_Time + Review_Cycle(weeks)*Assumptions:

1. IFSupplier_Lead_Time = NULL THENSupplier_Lead_Time= 0 days
2. IF Pick_Up_Lead_Time = NULL THENPick_Up_Lead_Time= 0 days
3. IF Supplier_Lead_Time +Pick_Up_Lead_Time = 0days THENSupplier_Lead_Time= 14 days
4. Wh Inbound Handling Days = 4 days
5. Shipping Window Delay:Default shipping window delay:3 daysIf Shipping window <= 6, delay =3 daysIf shipping window > 6, delay =window / 2(if the window is 14 days delay is 7 days)
6. If review frequency is null THEN review time 1. There is not any other capping or manipulations on dc review time.

# 4) Target Calculation

time 1. There is not any other capping or manipulations on dc review time.

# 4) Target Calculation

Invent determines store level needs in accordance with the store targets and DC Cover Period forecasts. While determining these needs store level inventory is considered too. Later, these needs are aggregated to related warehouses and the main body of the target is created. Lastly, the safety stock is added. Note that, if a store carries too much inventory no need is created for this store. This means Invent considers store level and system level inventories while creating DC targets.

The algorithm works like this:

1- Check store level targets and forecasts

2- Check store-level inventory and determine the raw store needs

3- Adjust the raw store needs in accordance with the Store Order Mult

4- Aggregate adjusted store needs and find the raw system need

5- Add safety stock to the adjusted system need, calculate the final target

ind the raw system need

5- Add safety stock to the adjusted system need, calculate the final target

6- If the ITEM-DC has a pres stock > final target, then the final target will be equal to pres stock

7- Use the final target while ordering (Casepack information is used while ordering)

1. The system will only use SUPP_PACK_SIZE info in Item_Supp_Country for package sizes while ordering for DC. The system will use SUPP_PACK_SIZE even if the Store_Ord_Mult is 'I' in ITEM_LOC for a product -
2. The system also checks the current store level needs and aggregates them to DC level in accordance with the store level pack size.
3. DC SOQ - raw = MAX(DC Target - DC Net Stock, 0)
4. DC SOQ is calculated by rounding DC SOQ - raw in accordance with DC Casepack. For example, if the DC SOQ - raw is 25 and the DC Case pack is 100, then the DC SOQ will be 100.
5. The threshold for case pack rounding is = 0.2. For example, if the case pack is 20 DC SOQ - raw = 24 is rounded to 20 andDC SOQ - raw = 25 is rounded to 40. (4/20 = 0.2, 5/20 = 0.25). This rounding threshold may change by item/store/time based on margin and sales pattern.

20 = 0.25). This rounding threshold may change by item/store/time based on margin and sales pattern.
6. While ordering all subitem inventory is taken into account. The Invent DC RPL system only creates SOQ for the main SKUs. Subitem inventory of the main SKU is counted as main SKU inventory.
7. If the NetStock = 0 and DC Target > 0, at least one case pack amount SOQ is created. (The threshold for case pack rounding becomes 0.001 in this case)

## Subitem use:

For DC replenishment, the sub-item relation will be determined using the product-store and product-DC relations. Use the product-store and product-DC sub item relations and resolve store level data at the item level.

1. If there is a review cycle more than a week, let's say every other week and day is Sunday. In this case, the engine will provide order each Sunday by using two weeks cover period. The assumption is, order generation will fail in the wrong week and will succeed in the other week.

Invent provides three filesFile1: Location-Item-TargetMin-TargetMaxFileFile2: DC to StoreOrdersFile3: XDock & Direct to StoreOrders&Vendor to DC ordersThese files are uploading & running during thedaily batch.We expect to have two different timing schedule:Morning batch*- ASO will upload File1 and the system will overwritereplitem loc Min Maxvalue and it will change the replenishment method to MinMax. If the location-item combination is not inreplitem loc, the system will create dummy parameters. (We should be aware that after this submission time if there is any change for the target by the user, Invent targets will be overwrittenby the user. We don't want to block that, it should be a rare case though)Night batch:- Oracle calculates orders for every store item combinations. Invent orders overwrites the Oracle orders. (if Invent has provided order)Assumptions- Providing targets and providing orders are independent processes from each other.

1. If Invent didn't provide any target the next day and if the user didn't make any change inreplitem loc, the system will naturally use the target thatInventprovided yesterday.Unless there is a scheduled target change that day
2. What will happen if Invent providesstore-itemcombination in Order file which doesn't have areplitem loc record?Oracle will not process those records and it will create an error log.
3. What will happen if Invent provides target less than pres stock? Invent doesn't need to change targets based on pres stock. Oracle will handle that part

# Result Review

## High-Level Executed Order Review

Objective:

In this report, the user can see the details of the orders that were created last night. In addition to order details, the reports have additional metrics such as recent period sales, store net inventory values, last year future period sales, etc. The objective of reviewing this report is to ensure that the ordered units and ordered cost are acceptable. The user can focus on any SKU or Store to see details such as Target values, Inventory quantities, sales, and forecast values.

This report allows users to answer questions about the acceptability of any order quantities or target levels; i.e. if they seem too high/too low. This report displays the details of the engine calculation including the RMS parameters that the engine is using. Users can utilize this report to identify RMS parameters that are incorrect allowing them to make corrections in RMS that will be effective the following day.

hat are incorrect allowing them to make corrections in RMS that will be effective the following day.

Review of this report should be a daily task.

# System Improvement

## Initial Inventory Push

Objective:The Invent engine will not initiate any initial shipments to stores. If a store-sku combination has never received initial inventory the Invent engine will not generate results as a failsafe against taking action against incorrect ranging information. The user should review the Store-SKU combinations which are active yet never received initial inventory and determine the reason for the omission. Potential reasons are:

never received initial inventory and determine the reason for the omission. Potential reasons are:

1. Item Loc Status might be wrong and should not be Active
2. Initial allocations inadvertently omitted this location
3. The location was only recently made Active and about to be allocated inventory
4. No Presentation Stock has been defined in RMS for that SKU-LOC

Once the reason has been determined the analyst is required to take corrective action, i.e. change item status, execute an allocation, set Presentation Stock, etc.

Related Reports: Replenishment / KPI Report / Daily InStock Rate / Store-SKU Needs Manual Push

Report Usage Explanation:[Reporting Guideline](https://invent.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/ASOCS/pages/905740289/Reporting+Guideline#ReportingGuideline-Store-SKUNeedsManualPush)

# Presentation Stock Process

Objective:

Presentation Stocks are the minimum quantity that you want on hand based upon capacity. At a minimum, Invent will send this quantity to the stores when orders are generated. Presentation Stocks are a key input to the Invent replenishment calculation. If they are overstated, then ASO will not achieve the optimal benefit of Invent Analytics. If they are understated, there is potential for an inadequate visual representation of the product.

Related User Interface Location & Input Instructions:

UI Location: RMS

User Interface LinkRelated Reports/Templates:Presentation Stock Setup Report/Template, Excess Inventory Report, Presentation Stock Input Alert Report

Report Usage Explanation: Reporting Guideline Link

y Report, Presentation Stock Input Alert Report

Report Usage Explanation: Reporting Guideline Link

- Presentation Stock Setup Report/Template (ABI) :The purpose of this report is to help the RA determine the optimal presentation stock quantity using space planning metrics.
- Excess Inventory Report (Tableau):The purpose of this report is to quantify excess inventory at cost being driven by presentation stocks (above and beyond the safety stock).
- Presentation Stock Input Alert Report (Tableau)The purpose of this report is to identify item/locations that might have excessively high or low presentation stock values (i.e.: fat fingers/keying errors)

Additional Reference Material:Replenishment Calculation Link (in fundamentals folder)

## Explanation:

ASO will submit one spreadsheet each week if there are any new items that we want to move in Invent engine. Invent system will automatically handle subitem relations. For example, if the user submits Item A today, and after a month she changes Item A with Item B and that input entered to RMS sub item table, Invent will automatically take that item in the scope.

1. Day Limit:LeadTime:If REPL_ITEM_LOC has a SUPP_LEAD_TIME for item-warehouse combination we take it. Otherwise, we look at ITEM_SUPP_COUNTRY and use LEAD_TIME. If neither of these has a record, we take 14as default lead time.PickupLeadTime = If REPL_ITEM_LOC has a PICKUP_LEAD_TIMEfor item-warehouse combination we take it. Otherwise, we look at ITEM_SUPP_COUNTRY and use PICKUP_LEAD_TIME. If neither of these has a record, we take 0 as default pick-up time.ReviewTime = We take both REVIEW_CYCLE and REPL_DAY into account. Review time is how many days there is until the next review date.For example, if REVIEW_CYCLEis 0 and REPL_DAY includes only one day as active, then ReviewTime is 7. If REVIEW_CYCLEis 0 and we have Monday, Wednesday, Saturday as active in REPL_DAY and today is Wednesday, then there are Saturday-Wednesday = 7th day of the week  4th day of the week= 3 days until the next review date

re Saturday-Wednesday = 7th day of the week  4th day of the week= 3 days until the next review date. If we don't have REVIEW_CYLE and REPL_DAY records we use 7 as default ReviewTime.CoverPeriod = LeadTime + PickupLeadTime + ReviewTimeDayLimit = CoverPeriod + 7 in order to enlarge the date scope a little bit and to be safer.

viewTimeDayLimit = CoverPeriod + 7 in order to enlarge the date scope a little bit and to be safer.
2. Incoming Orders:Orders in the ORDHEAD with 'A' statusare used to calculate IncomingStockFromSupplier.We use orders with that NOT_BEFORE_DATE is null orNOT_BEFORE_DATE is less than (<) DateOfTheStock + DayLimit.If we don't haveDayLimit information, we use 28as the default DayLimit.We use ORDLOC table for active orders and sum Max(QTY_ORDERED - QTY_RECEIVED, 0) by grouping records on ITEM-LOCATION. The sum is the incoming stock. (X)Then we look at ALLOC_HEADER to find out allocations that are defined on ITEM-WH combinations. We look at the allocations with 'A' status only.We use ALLOC_DETAIL table for active allocations and sum Max(QTY_ALLOCATED - QTY_TRANSFERRED - QTY_DISTRO, 0) by grouping records on ITEM-WH. The sum indicates how many quantities will be sent to stores after they are received. (Y)Then we calculate IncomingStockFromSupplier as (X) - (Y)

sent to stores after they are received. (Y)Then we calculate IncomingStockFromSupplier as (X) - (Y)

Cross Dock Orders: If order in ALLOC_HEADER has a not null ORDER_NO and its status is 'A', we take this order into account as a cross-dock order.We look at ALLOC_DETAIL table just for orders listed in Cross Dock Orders. -> Cross_Dock_Order_ALLOC_DETAILWe sum QTY_DISTRO by grouping records on ITEM-WH.OutgoingStock is written as sum(QTY_DISTRO)
4. Adjusted Non-Sellable Stock:Instead of using NON_SELLABLE_QTY coming in ITEM_LOC_SOH, we calculate non-sellable stocks using the query that is provided by Prasad. The code block is written below:

ate non-sellable stocks using the query that is provided by Prasad. The code block is written below:

```sql
SELECT ah.item,
       ah.wh,
       Least( MAX( Nvl( ol.qty_received, 0 ) ), SUM( ad.qty_allocated - Nvl( ad.qty_distro, 0 ) - Nvl( ad.qty_transferred, 0 ) ) ) SNP_NON_SELLABLE_QTY
FROM   ORDHEAD oh,
       ORDLOC ol,
       ALLOC_HEADER ah,
       ALLOC_DETAIL ad
WHERE  oh.order_no = ol.order_no AND
       oh.order_no = ah.order_no AND
       ol.item = ah.item AND
       ol.location IS NOT NULL AND
       ol.location = ah.wh AND
       ad.alloc_no = ah.alloc_no AND
       oh.status = 'A' AND
       ah.status = 'A' AND
       Nvl( ol.qty_received, 0 ) > 0 AND
       ad.qty_allocated > 0 AND
       ad.qty_allocated > ( Nvl(ad.qty_received, 0)
                            + Nvl(ad.qty_transferred, 0) ) AND
       ( ad.qty_allocated - Nvl( ad.qty_distro, 0 ) - Nvl( ad.qty_transferred, 0 ) ) > 0
GROUP  BY ah.item,ah.wh;

```sql
SELECT AH.ITEM,
	AH.WH,
	CASE WHEN MAX(ISNULL(OL.QTY_RECEIVED, 0)) < SUM(AD.QTY_ALLOCATED - ISNULL(AD.QTY_DISTRO, 0) - ISNULL(AD.QTY_TRANSFERRED, 0)) THEN MAX(ISNULL(OL.QTY_RECEIVED, 0))
		ELSE SUM(AD.QTY_ALLOCATED - ISNULL(AD.QTY_DISTRO, 0) - ISNULL(AD.QTY_TRANSFERRED, 0))
	END AS NON_SELLABLE_QTY
FROM temp.ORDHEAD OH
	INNER JOIN temp.ORDLOC OL
		ON OH.ORDER_NO = OL.ORDER_NO
	INNER JOIN temp.ALLOC_HEADER AH
		ON OH.ORDER_NO = AH.ORDER_NO AND
		OL.ITEM = AH.ITEM AND
		OL.LOCATION = AH.WH
	INNER JOIN temp.ALLOC_DETAIL AD
		ON AD.ALLOC_NO = AH.ALLOC_NO
WHERE OH.STATUS = 'A' AND AH.STATUS = 'A' AND
	ISNULL(OL.QTY_RECEIVED, 0) > 0 AND AD.QTY_ALLOCATED > 0 AND
	AD.QTY_ALLOCATED > (ISNULL(AD.QTY_RECEIVED, 0) + ISNULL(AD.QTY_TRANSFERRED, 0)) AND
	(AD.QTY_ALLOCATED - ISNULL(AD.QTY_DISTRO, 0) - ISNULL(AD.QTY_TRANSFERRED, 0)) > 0
GROUP BY AH.ITEM,AH.WH

# Handling Negative Values in the Inventory Position Calculation

The system will sum NetStock and NetIncomingStock first, and then it will take the maximum with zero. TotalNetStock = MAX( (NetStock+NetIncomingStock), 0)

For the subitem relations, each item will do this calculation separately and then the inventory will be summed by item family.

Example: An SKU-DC combination

a) NetStock = 5 & NetIncomingStock = 3

TotalNetStock = 8

b) NetStock = -5 & NetIncomingStock = 5

TotalNetStock = 0

c) NetStock = -20 & NetIncomingStock = 5

TotalNetStock = 0

NetIncomingStock = 5

TotalNetStock = 0

c) NetStock = -20 & NetIncomingStock = 5

TotalNetStock = 0

d) NetStock = -5 & NetIncomingStock = 12

TotalNetStock = 7

Example: An item family, P1 and P2 are in the same family

a) P1: NetStock = 5 & NetIncomingStock = 3 TotalStock = 8 before merging family stocks

P2: NetStock = 2 & NetIncomingStock = 4 TotalStock = 6 before merging family stocks

TotalNetStock = 14 for P1 and P2 after merging family stocks

b) P1: NetStock = -5 & NetIncomingStock = 5 TotalStock = 0 before merging family stocks

P2: NetStock = 2 & NetIncomingStock = 4 TotalStock = 6 before merging family stocks

TotalNetStock = 6 for P1 and P2 after merging family stocks

c) P1: NetStock = -15 & NetIncomingStock = 3 TotalStock = 0 before merging family stocks

P2: NetStock = 2 & NetIncomingStock = 4 TotalStock = 6 before merging family stocks

TotalNetStock = 6 for P1 and P2 after merging family stocks

## Calculation

1. The main Item - sub Item combinations are chosen usingSUB_ITEMS_DETAIL andSUB_ITEMS_HEAD tables. Records with CHANGED_OPS!= 'DELETE' are selected. (Records with both LOC_TYPE = 'S' and LOC_TYPE = 'W' are used.)
2. Family relations are created by grouping items. Records with links through the main or sub-item are grouped together.
3. The item which is declared as the Main Item and not declared as Sub Item inSUB_ITEMS_DETAIL is chosen as Main Item of the family.If there are more than one candidates to be the Main Item of the family, the item which is declared as Main in most of the locations is selected as Main Item of the family.

## Updating Family Table inProduction

We update family relation tables with a 1-day lag. Once we get new sub item files, we use them to extract new relations. However, we don't put new relations immediately in production. A control process works to detect changes in family relations. We update the family relations in production one day later.

s to detect changes in family relations. We update the family relations in production one day later.

Day 1: After daily data feed, new family relations are extracted. They are held in a temporary table. The control process works todetect changes between family relations in production and temporary relations. If anything wrong is detected, temporary relations are updated to fix problematic cases.

Day 2: Family relations in production are updated using temporary family relations. And the processes in Day 1 are completed.

The simplest explanation for the lost sales is "It is a weighted instock rate. Weighted by, Item sales speed, store sales speed, date sales speed.

Let's assume the system will calculate lost sales for Product Group-A for Week-T. We have 5 stores and 1 item (Product-X).

For that product group, below is the Store Sales Shares,

| Store Code | Store Sales Share in that Product Group-A | Product-X Week-T InStock Position | Product X, Week -T Sales |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| S1 | 15% | InStock | 2 |
| S2 | 20% | InStock | 0 |
| S3 | 15% | StockOut | 0 |
| S4 | 25% | StockOut | 0 |
| S5 | 25% | InStock | 4 |
| Total | 100% |  | 6 |

For Product-X, I can see that it was instock for 60% of the system and sold 6 units. We can assume that if the product was instock for 100% of the system, it was going to sell 10 units.

S3 has a lost sales as 10*15% = 1.5, S4 has a lost sales as 2.5 units.

Above is a very simple example. The lost sales engine tries to finetune the model to cover lots of detail such as:

- stock out day effect. It is different to be stock out on Sunday vs Wednesday
- similar store set to use as a reference for each stock out store. Store's behaviors don't have to be the same across all subclasses or products.
- outlier sales
- store-sku historical sales performance
- How to calculate the store share for each product
- ...etc.

The model calibrates itself with the instock stores vs actual sales and applies those learnings to stock-out stores.

The system creates an SOQ threshold to be safe during order generation.

Store SOQ Threshold:

Every day with the updated Target, the system creates and SOQ threshold as:

SOQ Threshold Raw= Target - (Total Net Inventory + Submitted Orders Yesterday - DailyForecast * 5)

SOQ Threshold Final= SOQ Threshold Raw rounded by casepack

- If somehow the user creates allocation out of the season, Invent will send those store-sku combinations again even if it is not in the season. we wouldn't expect to see it since it is out of season. no one should allocate inventory or it shouldn't be active + non-clearance in Item Loc, but it is always a potential.
- If the user makes another allocation in the season, Invent will send those records again even if they are already in the repl item loc. Normally, we shouldn't see a new allocation after the season started, but we don't block this to happen as a design. Jessicas note: Users allocate on top of Invent today in ASO allocation system. ers allocate on top of Invent today in ASO allocation system. If records sent again, we will reject.

ASO steps
1- Read Invent Store-SKU file

2- Join SKU season code, season start date, season end date from season tables. Activate Date in the repl item loc will be season start date-14

3- If the store-sku does not exist in Repl-Item Loc OR dates are deactive in repl item loc, create the record and fill the start date & end date based on season startdate-14 and season end date. Otherwise skip this step.

he start date & end date based on season startdate-14 and season end date. Otherwise skip this step.

4- ASO will log the Invent file that Invent sends to create repl item loc. Then a nightly batch will check these SKUs season information changes such as startdate end date. Whenever there is a change, ASO system will go to the repl item loc table and update the end date or start date with the new values. When an Item season codes turn to YA, the ASO system will remove those records from this log table. Some details: probably, ASO will need to keep this table as SKU-SeasonCode in that time to cover repeated seasonal items. Details will be clarified by ASO Development team

Scenario-4
If the item starts it's life as seasonal replenishment. the user wanted to change it to YA/ Invent Replenishment forselected doors. how it will work?

ment. the user wanted to change it to YA/ Invent Replenishment forselected doors. how it will work?

- The seasonal lifecycle will not be managed by location. So the behavior is same as Scenario-3

Scenario-5
If the item starts it's life in 50 doors in the first season. in the next season, the user wanted to change the ranging as 250 doors. how the system will work? 50 doors should have a repl item loc from the previous season. when we send 250 doors to create repl item loc, 200 of them will be created, 50 of them will be updated, right?

- When the first 50 store sku came in , ASO custom process would have setup the repl item loc. when 250 comes again, if the 50 exists and is active then it will reject that 50 & setup the remaining200 , if the 50 exists and not active then it will setup all 250 with the activate date/de-activate date based on season.

### Scope Selection

Following scopes will be selected using item eligibility file everyday.

- Only Forecasting Scope (FC_IND = 1(or NULL) & Invent_inventory_Decision_Scope = 0)
- Replenishment Item Scope (Invent_inventory_Decision_Scope = 1, Season = year round)
- DC Replenishment Item Scope (Invent_inventory_Decision_Scope = 1 & EXCLUDE_DC_RPL = 0(or NULL), Season = year round)
- Allocation Item Scope (Invent_inventory_Decision_Scope = 1, Season = not year round)

- Reorderpoint (ROP):a value used to determine how much inventory to order for a given SKU-Store. Also known as an Order-Up-To (OUT) value or Target. When doing an ordering review, the system compares each SKU-Stores reorderpoint to its current inventory position (on hand plus on order units). An order is placed if the inventory position is below the reorderpoint. Because ordering must adhere to casepack size, the resulting order may bring the inventory position above the reorderpoint.
- Casepack:also referred to as store order minimum (SOM), order multiple, or inner pack. It specifies the number of units of the item that are grouped into a single package for shipment to the store. A casepack of 1 unit is sometimes referred to as shipping in eaches. Casepacks are usually determined by the manufacturer, based on an analysis of what constitutes an economic order quantity (EOQ).

ed by the manufacturer, based on an analysis of what constitutes an economic order quantity (EOQ).
- Presentation Level (PL):also referred to as display minimum or presentation minimum; it specifies the minimum number of units of the item that should be present on the store shelf at all times. Calculated reorderpoints are adjusted upward to match the presentation level if necessary.
- Raw Reorderpoint:the optimal reorderpoint calculated before the application of a presentation level constraint.

oint:the optimal reorderpoint calculated before the application of a presentation level constraint.
- Expected Average On Hand:the average number of units of inventory we would expect to be on hand, given our reorderpoint (ROP), demand forecast (fcst), casepack , lead time (LT), and total coverage period (CP).               ExpOH=ROP+((Casepack1)(CPd+LTd))/2whereCPdis the expected demand over the next coverage period (defined as lead time plus review period), andLTdis the demand over the next lead time. This number should be viewed as a lower bound on the expected average on hand. In practice, on hand will generally be higher (due to seasonal peaks and forecast fluctuation).
- Excess Inventory:number of units of on hand inventory above the current reorderpoint plus a casepack.                ExcessInventory = MAX(OH  (ROP-1 + Casepack), 0)

F_Week: F_CP*7/Cover Period

Cover Period= Lead Time + Review Time

### Including allocation pairs into Maps RPL run

Current steps:

- take ReorderPoints of replenishment pairs from AcademyReporting.dbo.ReorderPointsTempTable and insert them into replenishment.ExternalReorderPointsAndOrderUptoLevels.
- create replenishment.CustomerPairs by filtering ROPs with replenishment.ActivePairs and replenishment.ActiveProductStoreRelations.

New version:

- take ReorderPoints of replenishment pairs from AcademyReporting.dbo.ReorderPointsTempTable and ReorderPoints of allocation pairs from AcademyReporting.dbo.AllocationReorderPointsTempTable, and insert them into replenishment.ExternalReorderPointsAndOrderUptoLevels.

- create replenishment.CustomerPairs by filtering ROPs with replenishment.ActivePairs and replenishment.ActiveProductStoreRelations. (nothing changes)

Promotion Data Feed Tables

Promotion information will be fed to Invent in two tables:

- The Promotion Definition Table, and

- the Promotion Assignment Table

Name for the files should be in the format of PromoFileIdentifier_PromotionDefinitionTable.csv (i.e. BBQ_May2020_PromotionDefinitionTable) and PromoFileIdentifier_PromotionAssignmentTable.csv.

The Promotion Definition Table gives details of a specific promotion. Each promotion is identified by a unique Promotion ID code.

The Promotion Assignment Table associates SKU-Stores with a promotion.

Updating Process

Invent will receive a daily refresh of the entire current promotion calendar, including any promotion that has not yet ended.

PromoIDs no longer present in a daily feed are presumed to be canceled

Promo Type Dictionary

ASO will provide a description of the promo types and associated parameters; this will be updated on an as-needed basis.

# Checklist

1. DO NOT use | (pipe, AKA vertical bar) anywhere in the file. Otherwise system will not be able process the submitted file.
2. ProductCode column must have left zero padding (9 characters)Wrong Input = 558  Correct Input = 000000558Correct Input = 1234567891  Correct Input = 1234567891 (its the same since its longer than 9 characters)
3. There must be only one record for a ProductCode. If there exists multiple records, system will not process the submitted file.
4. Our system will not check if ProductCode exists in RMS or not. If it doesn't, we will not process the ProductCode. In this case, we will process the Item Submission file but the ProductCode
5. Seasonality_Reference_Level column can have following values:ProductCodeStyle-DiffSubclassClassDept

Seasonality_Reference_Level column can have following values:ProductCodeStyle-DiffSubclassClassDept
6. Seasonality_Reference_Code column should have correct left zero padding. Otherwise we will process the file however system wont be able to find the seasonality reference if needed.If Seasonality_Reference_Level = ProductCode, left zero padding 9 characters.(See Checklist #1)If Seasonality_Reference_Level = Style-Diff, it should have the exact style diff definition as its in SAS.If Seasonality_Reference_Level = Subclass, left zero padding 4 characters.(See Checklist #1)If Seasonality_Reference_Level = Class, left zero padding 4 characters.(See Checklist #1)If Seasonality_Reference_Level = Dept, left zero padding 4 characters.(See Checklist #1)

hecklist #1)If Seasonality_Reference_Level = Dept, left zero padding 4 characters.(See Checklist #1)
7. Seasonality_Reference_Code column should have correct value. For example If Seasonality_Reference_Level = Dept, Seasonality_Reference_Code can not be a subclass code. In this case, we will process the Item Submission file but system wont be able to find the seasonality reference if needed.
8. Model_After_SKU column must have left zero padding(9 characters).
9. Model_After_SKU column can have only one ProductCode. If it has more than one ProductCode we will not use any of them.
10. Our system will not check if Model_After_SKU exists in RMS or not. If it doesn't, we will not process the Model_After_SKU. In this case, we will process the Item Submission file but system wont be able use model after information.

case, we will process the Item Submission file but system wont be able use model after information.
11. Model_After_Ratio column should have values between 0.1 and 2.5 . It must be a numeric value. NULL records will not be processed.Such values as: 50%  or 100% or 2 times will result in failure in the processing of Item Submission. If that happens none of the records in Item Submission file will be processed.If Model_After_Ratio is less than 0.1 or more than 2.5, we will process the file and record, however we will limit the ratio to be within [0.1 , 2.5] range. (We can be more flexible depending on the ASO teams request)
12. Invent_Order_Control is a BIT column. It could be either 0 or 1. We allow empty values as well. If its different than 0 or 1, then the process will fail. If that happens none of the records in Item Submission file will be processed.

he process will fail. If that happens none of the records in Item Submission file will be processed.
13. FC_IND is a BIT. It could be either 0 or 1. We allow empty values as well. If its different than 0 or 1, then the process will fail. If that happens none of the records in Item Submission file will be processed.
14. Invent_Inventory_Decision_Scope is a BIT. It could be either 0 or 1. We allow empty values as well. If its different than 0 or 1, then the process will fail. If that happens none of the records in Item Submission file will be processed
15. Invent_Scope_StartDate is a DATE column. The format must be YYYY-MM-DD. Example: 2020-02-15. If there is any invalid format, then the process will fail. If that happens none of the records in Item Submission file will be processed. (We allow NULL values as well, therefore it can be empty)

in Item Submission file will be processed. (We allow NULL values as well, therefore it can be empty)
16. EXCLUDE_DC_RPL is a BIT. It could be either 0 or 1. We allow empty values as well. If its different than 0 or 1, then the process will fail. If that happens none of the records in Item Submission file will be processed.
17. Force_YR_Repl is a BIT. It could be either 0 or 1. We allow empty values as well. If its different than 0 or 1, then the process will fail. If that happens none of the records in Item Submission file will be processed.
18. Disable_SKU_Store_Export is a BIT. It could be either 0 or 1. We allow empty values as well. If its different than 0 or 1, then the process will fail. If that happens none of the records in Item Submission file will be processed.
19. Custom_3 columns are string. DO NOT insert more than 30 characters into these columns.

New releases of the Allocation Approval User Interface are periodically made available for user testing at[academy.next.inventanalytics.com](http://academy.next.inventanalytics.com/).

For each new release, we include a list of what is new, fixes to known problems, current limitations, and our priorities for future enhancements.

## Notes for 5/8/2020 Release

What's New

- SAS UDAs have been added to both the filtering pane and aggregation drop downs
- Supplier descriptions are now included along with Supplier codes in the filter pane drop down
- Ability to remove backlogged approved order quantities

Fixes to Known Problems

- Selecting a row in one page of the product level grid is subject to any actions performed while in another page, which may result in unintended changes. This has been fixed so that going to another page now deselects all rows in the previous page.

Known Limitations/Issues

- Buyer code values are not currently populated

Prioritized new features

Prioritized new features

- Ability to remove excess units from backlogged approved order quantities
- Provide an indication that approved quantities exceed available warehouse inventory

## Notes for 4/30/2020 Release

What's New

- The filtering pane has been redesigned. With the new version:Only the attributes with selected values for filtering are displayedManaging of custom filters has been streamlined and simplifiedAll filter-related operations now have sub-second response time

Known Limitations/Issues

content:
## DC Algorithm

## Algorithm v1= new algorithm that will be used in production after test/approval

Algorithm v1:Based on expected store orders during DC coverageperiod calculated through simulations.

Algorithm v1:Since it's based on store orders volatility(safety stock) is separated into two components:

1. The volatility that comes from demand forecast volatility on store-level: This part is handled during simulation because store targets are determined to incorporate that information.
2. The volatility that comes from expected store order volatility on the DC level.

New version(v1) has two main improvements against version v0:

1. It's one to one integrated with store replenishment, any parameter changes done in store replenishment will reflect.
2. Stock-outs / insufficient inventory at DC is better handled.

in store replenishment will reflect.
2. Stock-outs / insufficient inventory at DC is better handled.

Algorithm v1calculates future store targets first and then it estimates the store orders. Let's say the store target is not changing in this example and it is 10 constantly.

Algorithm v1would round the forecast to case pack quantity and estimates the store order as 6 units.

Both versions rounds to the case pack. The only difference is that v0  does not do it for all stores, that's how it handles the volatility from the case pack.

If store inventory goes below the presentation stock in the future, algorithm v0 estimates the need as only one case pack for the store - product combination. Algorithm v1 adds more than one case packs to reach the presentation level. Let's say in the future store inventory will be 1 unit, the presentation level is 8 units, the case pack is 6 units, and the forecast after that period will be 0.

esentation level is 8 units, the case pack is 6 units, and the forecast after that period will be 0.

Algorithm v1would define the store need as round up ( (presentation level  - store net total stock ) / casepack ) *  casepack  = roundup( 7 / 6 ) * 6 = 12

## Legacy Algorithm (this part will be removed after we complete all the transition)

Algorithm v0= current algorithm in production

Algorithm v0:Based on expected store orders in the store coverage period and demand forecast in the DC coverage period

Algorithm v0:Since it's based on demand forecast, safety stock in DC comes from the volatility in demand.

Algorithm v0calculates store needs by summing the forecasts. It does not round up the forecasts to the case pack for all stores.

For example, the case pack is 6, store on-hand inventory 10 units, store target 10 units, forecast in dc cover period is 3 units, presentation stock is 1 unit.

units, store target 10 units, forecast in dc cover period is 3 units, presentation stock is 1 unit.

Algorithm v0would find the need by the formula; Today Store Orders + Forecast in dc cover period = RoundToCasepack(10 - 10+ 3) = 6

Algorithm v0 would define the store need as 6 units in this situation.

With this perspective, here is the rules to define Store-SKU combinations.

1. SeasonCode of the SKU should not be Year-Round (details here https://invent.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/ASOCS/pages/1440219137/Item+Solution+Scope+Clarification+Design#About-seasons%3A )

3. Item-Loc should be Active and Clearance Indicator should be N

5. Todays date should be between ActiveStartDate & ActiveEndDate-7
6. Items submitted via the item submission must satisfy below requirements:Inventory Decision must be equal to 1Invent Scope Start Date must be less than or equal to todays date.

1. Selected item-locations that are sourced by the DC.
2. Since we have not received inventory transactions since Tuesday night, we added expected transfers that are generated on Monday night to the store inventory position.
3. Using our forecasts we decreased inventory position based on probability of sales.
4. We filtered high speed item-locations that sell at least one unit every 2-3 days on average.
5. Not to consume too much inventory at the DC, we eliminated the item-dc combinations that might end up with low inventory at the DC.
6. To generate the order numbers we used the recent reorder points calculated on Tuesday.
7. Activity information (i.e. Item loc/repl item loc), store order multiple values, presentation levels etc. all inputs are based on Tuesday's data.
8. File priorities are based on the speed. The higher the sales frequency of the item-location the higher the priority.

How are we going to decide to send a seasonal item in Initial Allocation file vs Seasonal Replenishment File (which is transfer file)?

Space Constraint Check Alert Mail

Our system actively monitors whether there is a new store opening in the next two months and also track the stores that are opened in the previous two months. Whenever a store opening is within that time frame (-2 months, +2 months), it starts to record initial push for each SKU-Store combination.
The formula used in the engine for initial push is:

`Sales Unit + Inventory On Hand + Incoming Inventory` on day 0.
If the item is not pushed to the new store, our engines are not creating targets. We can change it to use PresStock instead, however, this is not a common case, because RMS is supposed to do the same thing, then the next day we'll see the initial push, so the end result is one day lag in target creation, but both systems would do the same thing unless there is a manual interaction.

Heres a reference for the store selection module: [Store Replenishment Module]

#### Target Update:

Heres a reference for the store selection module: [Store Replenishment Module]

#### Target Update:

- If the initial push is higher than targets of top seller stores(~top 20%) in the system, we are capping the target using other stores' targets for the same item, in case if the initial push was too high for some other reason.
- When the store builds up some history ~ 2 weeks instock & more than 5 days of positive sale, we are maintaining sales units. If the item is selling much better than the initial push, we will maintain sales using chain level target cap as a maximum.
